ng out that the passages M. M. Carlin quotes represent in one case a paraphrase and in the other a faithful rendering of certain lines written by the Russian poet A. S. Pushkin, and that paraphrases (e.g. Miss Deutsch's "the rose, romantic flower") are apt to be more pleasing to ladies and gentlemen than a plain literal translation (e.g. 'romantic roses' for romanticheskje rozy).





VLADIMIR NABOKOV





Palace Hotel

Montreux

Switzerland





TO: WILLIAM H. HOWE

CC, 2 pp.





Montreux, Jan